title: Weekend Top Ten #372
body:
Top Ten People to Blame for the Ending of Infinity War

With Avengers: Endgame hurtling towards us like a moon pulled out of orbit by a mad space gonad wielding a shiny marigold, I thought it prudent to reflect on the previous film. Avengers: Infinity War was a spiffing bit of comic book jiggery-pokery, with oodles of big laughs and mammoth punch-ups, but famously it ended on what could be termed “a bit of a downer”. Spoiler alert for one of the biggest and most-watched movies of all time, but at the climax of the film Thanos – that griddle-chinned purple bastard – clicked his fingers and half the MCU crumbled into dust, with characters such as Peter Parker, Doctor Strange, T’Challa, and Wanda Maximoff going all Ash Wednesday on us.

So obviously the big question is: who’s to blame? Which daft-arsed Avenger went and bollocksed up the biggest fight in history? Whose head should be on the block? Here, then, is the case for the prosecution: the ten people most at fault for literally killing half of all sentient life. I’d throw the book at them, except most of them are already become dust, blowing away, like a leaf on the wind, watch how they soar.

Oh god, now I’ve just remembered that death. Thanks a lot, Kevin Feige.

  1. Star-Lord: I mean, come on. Why did you hit him, Peter? Spider-Man had his glove off! He had the glove off, for God’s sake! Twat.
  2. Thor: he really, really should have gone for the head.
  3. Scarlet Witch: let’s face it, none of this would have happened if she’d killed Vision back in Edinburgh. Selfish, really.
  4. Vision: while we’re at it, maybe he should have stuck with Cap instead of flitting off to Scotland for a booty call. Keep it in your pants next time, Vis. If there is a next time, what with half your brain being ripped out and your girlfriend looking like the leftovers of an unattended barbecue.
  5. Gamora: FFS Gamora, who did you think he was going to chuck off the cliff? Not-Hugo Weaving saw it coming a mile off. And maybe next time don’t get so excited by a bloody flick-knife.
  6. Doctor Strange: literally gave up the Time Stone. Oh, I know, I know, he probably has some kind of grand plan, coz he cheated and looked at the end of book. But he still gave up the Time Stone.
  7. Nebula: could she not have waited five more minutes before explaining to Quill what happened to Gamora? Maybe? Also, if she’d just stuck with the Guardians instead of running off to try to murder her father – who’s, like, the most powerful warlord in the galaxy – then she wouldn’t have ended up as a hostage. Come on, lass! Think a bit in future, eh?
  8. Captain America: look, I’ll always and forever be Team Cap, but maybe he should have told Tony about Bucky a bit earlier? Maybe? I mean, Tony probably shouldn’t have literally tried to murder Bucky once he found out, but still.
  9. Loki: I’m inclined to say almost everything in the MCU is his fault, but for the moment let’s focus on him half-inching the Tesseract from Odin’s vault before Asgard exploded. He really is the worst brother.
  10. Tony Stark: literally everything is his fault.

I will report back once I’ve seen Endgame to state whether I think any or all of these paid for their actions. And if Death’s Head is in it.

  4. Vision: while we’re at it, maybe he should have stuck with Cap instead of flitting off to Scotland for a booty call. Keep it in your pants next time, Vis. If there is a next time, what with half your brain being ripped out and your girlfriend looking like the leftovers of an unattended barbecue.
  5. Gamora: FFS Gamora, who did you think he was going to chuck off the cliff? Not-Hugo Weaving saw it coming a mile off. And maybe next time don’t get so excited by a bloody flick-knife.
  6. Doctor Strange: literally gave up the Time Stone. Oh, I know, I know, he probably has some kind of grand plan, coz he cheated and looked at the end of book. But he still gave up the Time Stone.
  7. Nebula: could she not have waited five more minutes before explaining to Quill what happened to Gamora? Maybe? Also, if she’d just stuck with the Guardians instead of running off to try to murder her father – who’s, like, the most powerful warlord in the galaxy – then she wouldn’t have ended up as a hostage. Come on, lass! Think a bit in future, eh?
  8. Captain America: look, I’ll always and forever be Team Cap, but maybe he should have told Tony about Bucky a bit earlier? Maybe? I mean, Tony probably shouldn’t have literally tried to murder Bucky once he found out, but still.
  9. Loki: I’m inclined to say almost everything in the MCU is his fault, but for the moment let’s focus on him half-inching the Tesseract from Odin’s vault before Asgard exploded. He really is the worst brother.
  10. Tony Stark: literally everything is his fault.

I will report back once I’ve seen Endgame to state whether I think any or all of these paid for their actions. And if Death’s Head is in it.
